Absorption of dietary cholesterol from the intestine is an important part of <termsem="GO:0042632"> cholesterol homeostasis </term> and represents the initial step that allows dietary cholesterol to exert its <termsem="GO:0008152"> metabolic </term> effects .
A typical western diet contains relatively equal amounts of cholesterol and non-cholesterol sterols , mainly plant sterols , of which about 55 % of the dietary cholesterol is <termsem="GO:0050892"> absorbed </term> and retained compared to ~ 1 % of the dietary non-cholesterol sterols [ 1-3 ] .
